6. Difference between Flex box Layout and Grid Layout:

🔹 Flexbox

Flexbox is one-dimensional.
It works either:
In a row
OR in a column

Best for:
Navigation bars
Buttons
Small layouts
<!-- Refer Day-3 Examples -->

🔹 Grid

Grid is two-dimensional.
It works:
In rows
AND columns together

Best for:
Full page layouts
Complex designs

| Feature   | Flexbox         | Grid              |
| --------- | --------------- | ----------------- |
| Dimension | One-dimensional | Two-dimensional   |
| Direction | Row OR Column   | Rows AND Columns  |
| Best For  | Components      | Full Page layouts |
| Alignment | Easy alignment  | Exact/accurate placement |


<!-- Day-5 Covered Topics -->
1. What is CSS Grid?

CSS Grid is a two-dimensional layout system.

It allows you to design layouts using:
a. Rows
b. Columns
c. Both together

Unlike Flexbox (1D), Grid works in 2D (rows + columns).

2. Basic Grid Styling
.container {
  display: grid;
}

3.grid-template-columns: 

a. Defines number and size of columns.

.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 200px 200px 200px;
}

In above example : Creates 3 columns of 200px width each.

Real-Time Use

Used in:

Product cards (i.e in ecommerce websites)
Image galleries
Dashboard layouts

Using of fr (Flexible Unit) :
fr = fraction of available space.

Ex:
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr;
}

above example will Create 3 equal columns using fr unit.

4. Complete Basic Grid Example

<div class="container">
  <div class="box">1</div>
  <div class="box">2</div>
  <div class="box">3</div>
  <div class="box">4</div>
</div>

.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  gap: 15px;
}

.box {
  background: lightblue;
  padding: 20px;
  text-align: center;
}

output: 
1   2
3   4

5. grid-template-areas (Named Layouts)
a. Best for page layouts.

Ex:
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;
  grid-template-rows: 100px 1fr 80px;
  grid-template-areas:
    "header header"
    "sidebar content"
    "footer footer";
}

.header { grid-area: header; }
.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
.content { grid-area: content; }
.footer { grid-area: footer; }

Output Structure:
HEADER
SIDEBAR | CONTENT
FOOTER

Real Time Usage:
-> Complete website layouts
-> Admin dashboards
-> Blog pages

6. Responsive Grid Example:

.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
  gap: 20px;
}

<!-- Tabs/Ipads -->
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .container {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  }
}

<!-- Mobile Devices -->
@media (max-width: 480px) {
  .container {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
}

Outputs:

-> Desktop → 4 columns
-> Tablet → 2 columns
-> Mobile → 1 column

block block block block -> Desktop/PCs
block block -> Tabs/Ipads
block -> Tabs/Ipads

7. Auto-fit and Auto-fill Example:

Example:

<div class="responsive-grid">
      <div class="box">1</div>
      <div class="box">2</div>
      <div class="box">3</div>
      <div class="box">4</div>
      <div class="box">5</div>
    </div>

.responsive-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr));
  gap: 10px;
}

What it does:

Creates responsive/adjustble columns based on screen's width
Automatically adjusts number of columns
Minimum width = 250px
Maximum = 1fr

Used in:
Responsive product grids
Photo galleries

